Data Mining¶

How Do Sleeping Hours, BMIs, And Depression Severity Interact?¶

  • Fiona LU
  • fiona0304.lu@gmail.com

INTRODUCTION¶

Many studies highlight that sleep patterns are related to health in certain areas, including obesity (St-Onge, 2017) and mental health (Gottesmann, 2002). By examining the datasets published from the Nationa Health And Nutrition Examination Survey (the NHANES) from 2017 to March 2020, this report is going to explore how sleep hours inter-relate to depression severity and body mass index(BMI), as well as discussing the relationship among these elements.

METHODOLOGY¶

By using Python, this study will firstly import and prepare the following 5 datasets from the NHANES 2017-2022 for a further analysis:

  • Demographic Variables (P_DEMO)
  • Sleep Disorders (P_SLQ)
  • Body Measures (P_BMX)
  • Mental Health - Depression Screener (P_DPQ)

For privacy and data protection reasons (CDC, 2021), participants will be given a unique participant ID for the survey (i.e. Respondent Sequence Number(SEQN)) rather than using their real names for the questionnaire answers and exam results. The answers are confidential and voluntary. In addition, there is some limited access data that is not available to the general public, further mitigating potential misuse and privacy issues.

FINDINGS¶

Result 1 - Age and Sleeping Hours¶

The first result is about the relationship between ages of the participants and their sleeping hours on weekdays and weekends. It merges the relevant columns from the tables sleep and demo, returning the result of average sleeping hours for participants aged from 16 to 80 accordingly.

In [13]:
#select columns and rename for the sleep table
sleep_new = sleep[['SEQN','SLD012','SLD013']].dropna().\
rename(columns = {'SLD012':'weekday sleep hours', 'SLD013':'weekends sleep hours'})

#choose age values from the demo table
demo_age = demo[['SEQN','RIDAGEYR']].rename(columns = {'RIDAGEYR':'age'})

#merge tables
sleep_age = pd.merge(sleep_new, demo_age, on='SEQN', how='left')

#mean sleeping hours for different ages
sleep_age_mean = sleep_age.groupby('age')[['weekday sleep hours','weekends sleep hours']].mean().reset_index()
sleep_age_mean.head(3)

from bokeh.layouts import column

from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource, RangeTool, HoverTool

p = figure(width=800, height=300, x_axis_label='age', y_axis_label='average sleeping hours')

# show the results
show(p)

From the line graph, We can see that participants sleep more on weekends than on weekdays. Although both weekdays and weekends sleeping hours show fluctuations, weekdays sleeping hours show a downward trend till 60 years old, whereras weekends sleeping hours are more stable. Therefore, sleepig hours do relate to ages in weekdays.

RESULT 2 - Sleep Hours and Depression Severity¶

The second result is about the relationship between the BMI of the participatnts and thier depression severity based on the Patient Health Questionnaire (Kroenke and Spitzer, 2002) they did. It merges the relevant columns from the tables sleep and mental, returning the result of the sleep hours of the participants and their depression serverity.

The questionnaire has 9 symptom questions in total, each of them points range from 0 to 3, being associated with the response categories "not at all," "several days," "more than half the days," and "nearly every day” (CDC, 2021). The total score, ranging from 0 to 27, can be calculated for a complete response to the 9 symptom questions, which also incorporates DSM-IV depression diagnostic criteria (Spitzer et al.,1999).

A PHQ-9 score ≥10 has a sensitivity of 88% and a specificity of 88% for major depression, and the scores of 0, 5, 10, 15, and 20 represented 'none', 'mild', 'moderate', 'moderately severe', and 'severe depression', respectively.

In [18]:
mental_score = mental.round(1) #make the data more readable by removing 'e' 
mental_score = (mental_score.
                 loc[mental_score[['DPQ010','DPQ020','DPQ030','DPQ040','DPQ050','DPQ060','DPQ070','DPQ080','DPQ090']].
                     isin([0,1,2,3]).
                     all(axis=1)])

#add two columns: total score (named 'score') and its corresponding depression severity (named 'depression severity')
mental_score['score'] = mental_score[['DPQ010','DPQ020','DPQ030','DPQ040','DPQ050','DPQ060',
                                       'DPQ070','DPQ080','DPQ090']].sum(axis=1)

mental_score['depression_severity'] = pd.cut(
    x = mental_score['score'],
    bins=[-1, 4, 9, 14, 19, 27],
    labels=['none', 'mild', 'moderate', 'moderately severe', 'severe'],
)

sleep_mental = pd.merge(sleep_new, mental_score, on='SEQN', how='left').dropna(subset = 'score')
sleep_mental.head(3)

From the scatter plot, We can see that it does not show a strong correlation between the two elecments, which means the sleep hour by itself does not strongly correlates to the depression severity. This result is not surprising, since the sleeping pattern is one of the nine questions, there are other eight factors affecting the result. However, it is necessary to see if the sleeping hours of the participants align to their response to the sleeping pattern question, (which will be further explored in Result 3).

In addition, there are some other factors we should also take into consideration. For instance, during the process of data recording, to minimise data disclosure, the data for participants who have extreme sleeping hours (e.g. more than 14hr) is partially shown in the public dataset.

RESULT 3 - 'Trouble Sleeping' Response and Sleep Hours¶

The third result shows the relationship between the responses of the participants to 'DPQ030' concerning the frequency of experiencing'trouble sleeping or sleeping too much, and their sleep hours. It merges the relevant columns from the tables sleep and mental, returning the result of participants' responses to the 3rd question and their sleeping hours, the response category is:

0 - "not at all,"

1 - "several days,"

2 - "more than half the days," and

3 - "nearly every day.”

In [26]:
import pandas as pd
from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource, Whisker
from bokeh.plotting import figure, show
from bokeh.transform import factor_cmap

sleep_response['DPQ030'] = sleep_response['DPQ030'].astype(str)
response_category = list(sorted(sleep_response['DPQ030'].unique()))

# compute quantiles
qs = sleep_response.groupby('DPQ030')['weekday sleep hours'].quantile([0.25, 0.5, 0.75])
qs = qs.unstack().reset_index()
qs.columns = ['DPQ030', 'q1', 'q2', 'q3']
new = pd.merge(sleep_response, qs, on='DPQ030', how="left")

# compute IQR outlier bounds
iqr = new.q3 - new.q1
new["upper"] = new.q3 + 1.5*iqr
new["lower"] = new.q1 - 1.5*iqr

source = ColumnDataSource(new)

p = figure(x_range=response_category, tools='hover', toolbar_location=None,
           title='DPQ030(Trouble Sleeping) Response and Sleep Hours',
           background_fill_color="#eaefef", y_axis_label='sleep hours',x_axis_label='response',
          tooltips = [('SEQN', '@SEQN'), ('q1', '@q1'),
                     ('q2', '@q2'), ('q3', '@q3')] )

# outlier range
whisker = Whisker(base='DPQ030', upper="upper", lower="lower", source=source)
whisker.upper_head.size = whisker.lower_head.size = 20
p.add_layout(whisker)

# quantile boxes
cmap = factor_cmap('DPQ030', "TolRainbow7", response_category)
p.vbar('DPQ030', 0.7, "q2", "q3", source=source, color=cmap, line_color="black")
p.vbar('DPQ030', 0.7, "q1", "q2", source=source, color=cmap, line_color="black")

# outliers
outliers = new[~new['weekday sleep hours'].between(new.lower, new.upper)]
p.scatter('DPQ030', 'weekday sleep hours', source=outliers, size=6, color="black", alpha=0.3)

p.xgrid.grid_line_color = None
p.axis.major_label_text_font_size="14px"
p.axis.axis_label_text_font_size="12px"

show(p)

From the box-plot above, we can see that for participants whose responses are 'nearly every day'(3.0 groups) to the question, showing a more fluctuated distribution of sleep hours, whereas 'not at all' groups (who do not have troubles sleeping) exhibit a more stable range of sleep hour. Moreover, in terms of medians, the '3.0' group has a comparatively lower number than other three response groups. Therefore, participants' responses to the 'trouble sleeping' question align with their sleeping hours, especially for the group of participants who have trouble sleeping nearly everday.

RESULT 4 - Obesity and Sleep Hours¶

The 4th result is about the sleep hours of the participants whose BMIs are catogorised into different categories. participants' BMIs will be further classified based on the BMI categories defined by the WHO:

• underweight if below 18.5

• normal range up to 25

• overweight above 25

• obese above 30

By merging the table sleep_new and bmi, it will return the result, showing how sleep hours distributed among different bmi catogories.

In [29]:
body_measures['category'] = pd.cut(x = body_measures['BMXBMI'],
                                   bins=[0, 18.5, 25, 30, np.inf],
    labels=['underweight', 'normal', 'overweight', 'obese'],
)
bmi = body_measures[['SEQN','BMXBMI','category']].dropna(subset = 'BMXBMI').\
rename(columns = {'BMXBMI':'BMI'})

sleep_bmi = pd.merge(sleep_new, bmi, on='SEQN', how='left').dropna()

from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource, Whisker
from bokeh.plotting import figure, show
from bokeh.transform import factor_cmap, jitter

bmi_category = list(sorted(sleep_bmi['category'].unique()))

p = figure(height=400, x_range=bmi_category, background_fill_color="#efefef",
title='Obesity and Sleep Hours', tools='hover', tooltips=[('SEQN', '@SEQN'), 
                                                          ('bmi', '@BMI'), ('category', '@category')])
p.xgrid.grid_line_color = None

g = sleep_bmi.groupby('category')
upper = g['weekday sleep hours'].quantile(0.80)
lower = g['weekday sleep hours'].quantile(0.20)
source = ColumnDataSource(data=dict(base=bmi_category, upper=upper, lower=lower))

error = Whisker(base="base", upper="upper", lower="lower", source=source,
                level="annotation", line_width=2)
error.upper_head.size=20
error.lower_head.size=20
p.add_layout(error)

p.circle(jitter('category', 0.3, range=p.x_range), 'weekday sleep hours', source=sleep_bmi, 
         alpha=0.5, size=8, line_color='white', color=factor_cmap('category', "Light7", bmi_category))

# show the results
show(p)

From the box plot above, we can see that 'normal', 'obese' and 'overweight' groups have a similar pattern in terms of the sleep hour ranges. However, the sleep hour of the 'underweight' group spans larger.

RESULT 5 - Obesity and Depression Severity¶

The results above focuses on how sleep hours interacts with obesity and mental conditions, but it will also be important to see if there is any relationship between obesity and mental conditions, which will be examined in the 5th section.

By merging the table mental_score and bmi and compute some aggregations, it will return the result of how many unique combinations of pairs (bmi_category, depression_severity) are there, along with their percentages to see how the two factors relate to each other.

In [34]:
body_measures['category'] = pd.cut(x = body_measures['BMXBMI'],
                                   bins=[0, 18.5, 25, 30, np.inf],
    labels=['underweight', 'normal', 'overweight', 'obese'],
)
bmi = body_measures[['SEQN','BMXBMI','category']].dropna(subset = 'BMXBMI').\
rename(columns = {'BMXBMI':'BMI'})

bmi_mental = pd.merge(bmi, mental_score[['SEQN','score','depression_severity','DPQ050']], 
                      on='SEQN', how='left').dropna()
bmi_mental_g = bmi_mental.groupby(['category','depression_severity']).size().reset_index(name = 'count')

bmi_mental_g['percent'] = (bmi_mental_g['count'] / bmi_mental_g.groupby('category')['count'].transform('sum'))*100

bmi_mental_g

from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource

dep_cates = list(sorted(bmi_mental_g['depression_severity'].unique()))

p = figure(x_range=bmi_cates, height=500,
           title='BMI category and Depression Severity',toolbar_location=None, 
           tools='hover', tooltips = [('Depression Severity','@depression_severity'),
                                      ('Counts','@count'), ('Percent','@percent %')])

p.vbar(x='category',top='count',source=source, width=0.5, 
       fill_color=factor_cmap('depression_severity', palette=Spectral5, factors=dep_cates), 
       legend_field='depression_severity')


p.xgrid.grid_line_color = None
p.y_range.start = 0
p.yaxis.axis_label = 'count'
p.xaxis.axis_label = 'BMI category'
p.legend.location = 'top_left'

show(p)

From the bar chart, we can see that the number of 'severe' and 'moderately severe' has the largest proportion in the 'obese' group comparatively, whereras 'moderate' has the highest percentage(13.04%) in 'underweight' group. Therefore, bmi categories do relates to the depression severity, for those abnormal categories, it will exhibit a higher risk in mental health.

CONCLUSION¶

To sum up, sleepig hours relate to ages in weekdays. The sleep hour by itself does not strongly correlates to the depression severity. BMI does not highly relates to sleeping hours, while participants' responses to the 'trouble sleeping' question align with their sleeping hours, especially for the group of participants who have trouble sleeping nearly everday. And bmi categories do relates to the depression severity, for those abnormal categories, it will exhibit a higher risk in mental health.
